\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider the likelihood of a participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,N]$
\end_inset

 winning in a competition that rewards only a privately known raw talent
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 hopkinsWhichInequality2010 discuss about a similar competition (all-pay
 auction).
 We assume that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r_{i}\}_{i\in[1,N]}$
\end_inset

 is a total order so that the maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 would win the raw-talent competition.
 In other words, the winner would be a player 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r_{i}<r_{j}\forall i\in[1,N]\}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based only on raw-talent, the probability that a given participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of raw-skill 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the winner is essentially that of all other players 
\begin_inset Formula $j\ne i$
\end_inset

 having ability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j\ne i}$
\end_inset

 less than 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the probability that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}{P(r_{i}>r_{1})\times P(r_{i}>r_{2})\times...P(r_{i}>r_{i-1})\times P(r_{i}>r_{i+1})...P(r>r_{N})}dr_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a uniform distribution of skills 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(r_{i}\ge r)=r_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,N]$
\end_inset

 and therefore, the above integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}{(r_{i})^{N-1}}dr_{i}=\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

.
 With more players, the chances of a particular participant winning declines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a swordfighter passes away, a new elite member is to be selected based
 on the random pick of both raw talent and acquired skills.
 We consider a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 that combines skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 so that the maximum score 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r+(1-\mu)s$
\end_inset

 wins the competion.
 Notice that the skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are rewarded only for a cost.
 Unlike hopkinsWhichInequality2010, we also the institutional bias in the
 model.
 The discrimination exists for a poor consumer only because skills acquired
 for every competition cost something to the consumer who is bounded by
 a finite budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Continuous model with choice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hopkins do talk about a similar model.
 Our model differs primarily due to consideration of budget constraints
 for choice.
 Consider distribution of raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 as before.
 But consider also the price of skills 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 so that a budget 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can be used to obtain the mutlitplier 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\nu,\pi)>1$
\end_inset

 and skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s\times c(\nu,\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 The multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\nu,\pi)$
\end_inset

 is an increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 so that higher costs are implied for more enhanced skills.
 We relive the assumption that no skills are obtained when 
\begin_inset Formula $y<\pi$
\end_inset

 .
 The participants face the choice to save towards assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 or expend on skills to improve their chances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 participants in the game, out of which 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are poor and obtained disposable income 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 in two periods.
 No income is saved towards end of life and thus the poor and rich participants
 spend 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 towards the culturally-curated skills respectively.
 The first-period is the only one where participants choose between savings
 and enhancing skills.
 In this first-period, the poor participant realises that she may be ahead
 of others in the competitions with a certain probability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To win, a poor participant must have her raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 ahead of all every one else - both rich and poor.
 Similarly, the rich consumer also participates while realising a probability
 of being ahead of both rich and poor.
 The difference between skills and raw-talent - is only that the former
 can be enhanced with more investment whereas raw-talent does not change
 with institutional advantages (or is too easy for the participant to develope
 on her own when needed).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When considering the poor participant, the conditional probability that
 she wins the competitions for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r_{i},s_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
P_{1}(\text{win}|r_{i},s_{i})=\prod_{k=1,k\ne i}^{k=P-1}{P(r_{i}\mu+s_{i}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{1},\pi)>r_{k}\mu+s_{k}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{1},\pi))}\\
\prod_{k=P+1}^{k=N}{P(r_{i}\mu+s_{i}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{1},\pi)>r_{k}\mu+s_{k}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{2},\pi))}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the conditional probability that a rich consumer wins the competition
 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r_{i},s_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
P_{2}(\text{win}|r_{i},s_{i})=\prod_{k=1}^{k=P-1}{P(r_{i}\mu+s_{i}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{2},\pi)>r_{k}\mu+s_{k}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{1},\pi))}\\
\prod_{k=P+1,k\ne i}^{k=N}{P(r_{i}\mu+s_{i}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{2},\pi)>r_{k}\mu+s_{k}(1-\mu)c(\nu_{2},\pi))}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the participant do not use the skill level 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 or the raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 to make the investment decision and that both skills and raw-talent are
 revealed to the participants upon participation in the competition.
 Therefore, all poor consumers and all rich consumers have the same behaviour
 regardless of their private 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Further, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

are independent since raw-talents are not enhanced by skills-granting institutio
ns by their very definition.
 The total probability of a win either for poor or rich participants is
 simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{s_{i}}P(\text{win}|s_{i})P(s_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{win}|s_{i})=\int_{r_{i}}P(win|(s_{i},r_{i}))P(r_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 If we represent densities of conditional probability of winning for given
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\text{win}|r_{i},s_{i})$
\end_inset

 then the above probability of winning for the poor participant is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{s_{i}}{(\int_{r_{i}}{P_{1}(\text{win}|s_{i},r_{i})P_{1}(r_{i})})P_{1}(s_{i})}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the probability of winning for a rich participant is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{s_{i}}{(\int_{r_{i}}{P_{2}(\text{win}|s_{i},r_{i})P_{2}(r_{i})})P_{2}(s_{i})}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uniform distribution
